For SEOs, especially if you're optimizing for vertical search (eg: video, audio, etc), it's important to understand how much personalization will affect a user's query results.

eg: skipping a track in their music player is a datapoint they log.
The other importance of CatBoost, and you see this _kind_ of thig a lot in the query handling, is that it _seems_ to be used heavily when it comes to personalizing search results.

Combined with a lot of code I browsed that stores and uses host and domain-level scoring, I would _infer_ that sites that are more categorically corralled - both in terms of content and backlinks - will help to make your site/pages more relevant for queries in that category.

It would then be possible to, again, in a very broad sense, "slice" the doc index at query time to rank search results by selecting/ranking higher documents from a subset of their entire index, which "categorically" matches a user's query.

What does this mean for SEO?

So, by logging all of their users' search queries, they can also create an index of those queries, and apply similar categorical ML models to them.

And instead of just an index for documents, there's also an index for queries.

And that can be put through similar ML analyses.

In very, very, very general terms... being a form of a decsion tree, CatBoost can, in a sense, "slice up" an index categorically.

Relevant categories can be determined both by the content in the index, as well as matching them up to your query.

In terms of search, it looks to me like the importance of CatBoost is primarily in two areas:

- Document Relevance/Ranking

- Query Personalization
In some very loose sense, queries are being de-clarified/muddied/generalized now before being sent to the search index (as well as actually ranking in the index).

I also believe this is why more technical users of search have become increasingly unhaopy with search results, as it has also become more difficult for a user to tailor their search results by refining their query.
So a user's query is, in some very broad sense, "expanded" and "interpreted" beyond the words that are used in the query, when searching for relevant documents.

Given that CatBoost is used more heavily on the indexing side, the importance here for SEOs is to know that, with BERT, a user's search queries aren't being searched directly on the document index like a traditional TF-IDF or BM25 algorithm.
BERT is used a _lot_ throughout both the query parsing/interpretation, as well as the document indexing and ranking.

Eager loading (.Include) can bring a massive performance boost in #efcore.

Is there a solution? Use filtered include when possible.

I expect my numbers will normalize as I send more queries.
BTW, if you can think of any ways to improve this query format, please hit me up here--I'm always down to improve my game!

QUERY ELEMENTS

There is no simple answer to this. A good query will be tailored to the recipient.

Most of mine are cold queries to people who don't know me and I don't know them. In other words, little or no personal commonality. I try to connect w/their work in some loose way.

It also automatically calculates 6 weeks from the query date, so I can mark it as a rejection if they don't respond.

This is, admittedly, inefficient. I'm working on a better way to run it, but the information is scattered; a cohesive system is a technical challenge.

HOW I TRACK QUERIES

I currently track everything in Google Sheets. I note the person, their email and phone (company phone is fine). I note what their title is and what company they're with, and I also link their IMDBPro URL.

I also note the script name + the date. https://t.co/4DrBNzHxLC

@donwinslow @SarahHuckabee this "PIC" would be the query to a "Daily-Double" answer on "Jeopardy" thus, "what is the difference between an obnoxious Liar and a domestic terrorist(daesh of the americas)"???

HOW I CHOOSE WHO TO QUERY

I have a super scientific method.

If I'm querying producers, I'll look up movies similar to the one I'm querying with. I'll make a gigantic list of everyone.

I put those names and IMDB profile addresses into a spreadsheet.
I then hunt for emails.

There's no real tip to getting rejected. Even the most compelling email query may be disregarded by its intended recipient.

A cold query has an extremely low rate of response of < than 2%.

The exciting rejections are when they ACTUALLY REPLY. 

This is considered a win. https://t.co/qDvLsIjgpd
